{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1053"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1053"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.1,0.14,0.18,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103664"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1053"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1053"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"194"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"650"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1372"},{"type":"tags","id":"2245"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"6518"},{"type":"tags","id":"7864"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103664"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle crash in which he was the restrained driver, hit by a side impact from another vehicle failing to stop at traffic lights. He describes right-sided chest pain, worse on breathing and with movement. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on 6 L/min oxygen via face mask, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His trachea is midline. There is tenderness over his right chest laterally, with sharp localised pain worsening on inspiration. A chest CT scan is performed, confirming a haemopneumothorax and several rib fractures in the area of chest wall tenderness (Images 1-2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely major contributor to this patient\u0027s pleuritic chest pain?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rib fractures","Pulmonary contusion","Pneumothorax","Haemothorax","Pericardial effusion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained significant chest trauma with multiple injuries visible on CT, including rib fractures and a haemopneumothorax. Whilst cases of primary spontaneous pneumothorax will often be accompanied by significant pleuritic pain, in the setting of trauma \u003Cstrong\u003Erib fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are usually the predominant source of pain. In this case of blunt chest trauma and localised tenderness of the area of the rib fractures, apart from there being severe localised pain it will be worsened with breathing or movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary contusion\u003C/strong\u003E represents bruising of lung tissue following blunt trauma. While it can cause respiratory compromise and hypoxia, it typically causes less pain than rib fractures. The pain from contusion tends to be deep and constant rather than sharp and pleuritic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can cause chest pain and breathlessness but typically produces a more constant, pressure-like discomfort rather than the sharp, movement-related pain described here. The pain is usually less severe than that of rib fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemothorax\u003C/strong\u003E similarly causes less acute pain than rib fractures, though it is a serious condition requiring urgent management, particularly given this patient\u0027s tachycardia and hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a dull, constant retrosternal discomfort rather than sharp, localised pleuritic pain. It is also less common in blunt chest trauma compared to the other injuries listed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile this patient has multiple thoracic injuries requiring urgent management, the rib fractures are the most likely direct cause of his pleuritic chest pain. The other conditions, while serious, typically cause different pain patterns or primarily present with other symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rib fractures are typically the primary source of pain in blunt chest trauma, causing localised pleuritic pain.","CT chest is the gold standard for diagnosing thoracic injuries in trauma, allowing visualization of rib fractures and associated complications."],"references":["Kuo K, Kim AM. Rib Fracture. In: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2022 Aug 8]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541020/","He Z, Zhang D, Xiao H, Zhu Q, Xuan Y, Su K, Liao M, Tang Y, Xu E. The ideal methods for the management of rib fractures. J Thorac Dis. 2019 May;11(Suppl 8):S1078-S1089. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6545517/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19241"},{"type":"media","id":"19242"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19241"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29ae5847-b201-4f7a-8b94-f34cf80f7b92.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/29ae5847-b201-4f7a-8b94-f34cf80f7b92.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":538,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19242"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/09f54243-f1e5-494f-8e9c-660e7d1d1a64.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/09f54243-f1e5-494f-8e9c-660e7d1d1a64.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":500,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T15:16:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T15:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1053"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103664"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"